/ lees	,
https://www.centos.org/forums/viewtopic.php?t=62352

When I left my computer alone yesterday, the screen went black (just normal case) after a few minutes, but I was not able to bring system back. Youtube in Google Chrome was still playing but I had only a mouse and black screen. I logged out using ctrl+alt+F5 and than I typed init 5
I saw centos logo and spinning wheel. Later I think that everything crashed, I was not able to use keyboard.

systemctl restart gdm.service should work. if its nonlogin u can try with ssh.

Also read /var/log/messages and /var/log/secure and see if either have entries around the relevant times.

/ 7	. 

$ vi /etc/yum.repos.d/google-chrome.repo

[google-chrome]
name=google-chrome
baseurl=http://dl.google.com/linux/chrome/rpm/stable/x86_64
enabled=1
gpgcheck=1
gpgkey=https://dl.google.com/linux/linux_signing_key.pub

/ we lezen op 	,
https://www.if-not-true-then-false.com/2010/install-google-chrome-with-yum-on-fedora-red-hat-rhel/

[google-chrome]
name=google-chrome - \$basearch
baseurl=http://dl.google.com/linux/chrome/rpm/stable/\$basearch
enabled=1
gpgcheck=1
gpgkey=https://dl-ssl.google.com/linux/linux_signing_key.pub

/ 7	. 

/ rpmsave, rpmnew

/ lees	,
https://serverfault.com/questions/48776/why-do-i-have-rpmnew-file-after-an-update

If a file was installed as part of a rpm, it is a config file (i.e. marked with the %config tag), you've edited the file afterwards and you now update the rpm then the new config file (from the newer rpm) will replace your old config file (i.e. become the active file). The latter will be renamed with the .rpmsave suffix.
If a file was installed as part of a rpm, it is a noreplace-config file (i.e. marked with the %config(noreplace) tag), you've edited the file afterwards and you now update the rpm then your old config file will stay in place (i.e. stay active) and the new config file (from the newer rpm) will be copied to disk with the .rpmnew suffix.

/ file.rpmsave is de oude config file, de nieuwe heet file	, 
/ we moeten file.rpmsave merge in file, en file.rpmsave weggooien	,

/ de oude config file blijft file, en de nieuwe config file heet file.rpmnew
/ we moeten file merge in file.rpmnew, en file.rpmnew rename naar file	,

/ 7	. 

/ Ik deed iets en gnome rotated	, 

/ lees,
https://ask.fedoraproject.org/en/question/92300/how-do-i-fix-my-display-which-has-rotated-180-degrees-after-login/

[eric@almond ~]$ xrandr --listmonitors
Monitors: 1
 0: +*LVDS1 768/340x1366/190+0+0  LVDS1
[eric@almond ~]$ xrandr --output LVDS1 --rotate <tab>
inverted  left      normal    right     
eric@almond ~]$ xrandr --output LVDS1 --rotate normal
/ Weer OK 

/ Lees	,
https://help.gnome.org/users/evince/stable/shortcuts.html.en

/ 7	. 

/ mail in fedora	,

/ google,
fedora 25 mail
/ lees	,
https://docs.fedoraproject.org/f26/system-administrators-guide/servers/Mail_Servers.html
[eric@almond second]$ sudo vi /etc/postfix/main.cf
myhostname = almond.nuts.org
mydomain = nuts.org
# SENDING MAIL
myorigin = $mydomain
# RECEIVING MAIL
#inet_interfaces = localhost            # commented out ,
inet_interfaces = all
mynetworks = 192.168.123.128/28, 127.0.0.0/8

[eric@almond second]$ sudo systemctl restart postfix

/ google 
fedora test postfix
/ lees	,
https://fedoraproject.org/wiki/QA:Testcase_Postfix

/ 7	. 

[eric@almond dockerfile]$ cat 
foo
foo													/ geef ctrl-d
[eric@almond dockerfile]$ cat onhost.txt 
foo bar on host
/ hier zien we goed het verschil tussen stdin en arg aan cat	,
/ de content van arg is als stdin	,
/ als je arg wilt, gebruik dan xargs in pipe:
[eric@almond dockerfile]$ echo onhost.txt | cat
onhost.txt
[eric@almond dockerfile]$ echo onhost.txt | xargs cat
foo bar on host

/ 7	. 

/ lees	,
https://www.redhat.com/archives/rhl-list/2003-December/msg04713.html

The 'new' default file from the update package is installed as rpmnew and might reflect new options or a new notion of best practices.

In such cases the new might be installed and your old file renamed as something.rpmsave.  

/ bij rpmnew WH $ mv .rpmnew  <orig>
/ bij rpmsave WH $ rm .rpmsave 

/ 13	. 

So check your upgrade.log and search for *.rpmnew *.rpmsave on
your system.

Check the log:

	egrep "rpmnew|rpmsave" /root/upgrade.log

A quick system wide search trick is to use the slocate data base
that is updated once a day:

	locate rpmnew
	locate rpmsave

Or do full system search with find, something like:

	find / -print | egrep "rpmnew$|rpmsave$"

/ 13	. 

There are multiple tools for showing and resolving the
differences between two files.  This week I like the -d option
of vim. I always start in read only mode, example:

   vim -R -d  /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf.rpmnew  /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf

I still use diff a lot.  Example:

   diff  /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf.rpmnew   /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf

/ 13

/ CHROME

/ lees	,
https://tecadmin.net/install-google-chrome-in-centos-rhel-and-fedora/

[chrome]
name=google-chrome
baseurl=http://dl.google.com/linux/chrome/rpm/stable/x86_64
enabled=1
gpgcheck=1
gpgkey=https://dl-ssl.google.com/linux/linux_signing_key.pub

/ lees	,

cat << EOF > /etc/yum.repos.d/google-chrome.repo
[google-chrome]
name=google-chrome
baseurl=http://dl.google.com/linux/chrome/rpm/stable/x86_64
enabled=1
gpgcheck=1
gpgkey=https://dl-ssl.google.com/linux/linux_signing_key.pub
EOF

dnf install google-chrome-stable

/ SUDO

/ lees,
https://docs.fedoraproject.org/en-US/quick-docs/adding_user_to_sudoers_file/

[eric@almond my]$ groups
eric wheel docker

On Fedora, it is the wheel group the user has to be added to, as this group has full admin privileges. Add a user to the group using the following command:
$ sudo usermod -aG wheel username
/ TODO

$ sudo visudo
...
%wheel ALL=(ALL) ALL
...

/ we zien op almond	,
## Allows people in group wheel to run all commands
%wheel  ALL=(ALL)       ALL

## Same thing without a password
%wheel  ALL=(ALL)       NOPASSWD: ALL

/ daarom kan WH	,
[eric@almond postgres3a]$ sudo su - postgres
-bash-4.4$ exit
